      <title>3D-printed prosthetic limbs used to treat war amputees</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANDoctors looking to 3D technology to provide prosthetic access to poor and wounded refugees in the Middle East.Mdecins Sans Frontires, or Doctors Without Borders, has been working with a hospital in Amman, Jordan to help upper-limb amputees from war-torn nations.Before designing a prosthetic limb, the team assesses each patient and makes a scan of their stumps.They use flexible thermoplastic polyurethane to 3D-print the socket and hand, and a firmer plastic to create the forearm. The 3D printed prosthetics take only 24 hours to design and produce and costs only a fraction of the normal price at $20.When the parts have been assembled together, the limb can be painted to match the patient's skin tone.Doctors make sure the lightweight prosthetic limb fits comfortably on the stump, ensuring patients will be able to use it long-term, according to their needs. Doctors Without Borders is still improving the process, but wants to expand to other missions in the future.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Doctors without Borders helping war-wounded patients in Jordan2. Prosthesis for upper-arm amputees designed based on patient needs3. Depiction of 3D-printed prosthetic parts 4. Customizable prosthetic parts coming together5. Patient fitted with prosthetic armVOICEOVER (in English): "Doctors Without Borders has been working with a hospital in Amman, Jordan to help upper-limb amputees from war-torn nations.""Before designing a prosthetic limb, the team assesses each patient and makes a scan of their stumps.""They use flexible thermoplastic polyurethane to 3D-print the socket and hand, and a firmer plastic to create the forearm.""When the parts have been assembled together, the limb can be painted to match the patient's skin tone."SOURCES: Doctors Without Borders, New Atlashttp://rsp.msf-me.org/en/index.htmlhttps://www.msf.org.uk/video/innovation-3d-printed-prosthetic-limbs-refugeeshttps://newatlas.com/3d-printed-prostheses-syria/53685/***]]></description>
