      <title>The best way to charge your smartphone</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANTime reports that modern smartphones use lithium-ion batteries that charge fast but also get used up quickly because of the sheer amount of mobile activity they power.People tend to drain their phone batteries before plugging them in overnight. Fortunately, most are equipped with chips that protect against overcharging.Still, it's unwise to leave a device plugged once its battery is full, since trickle charges can heat up the phone, stressing and wearing down the battery.Experts recommend charging the phone before it empties completely, and not bringing it to a full charge. Plugging it in occasionally throughout the day ensures the battery retains its capacity longer.Batteries also don't do well in extreme heat or extreme cold, so make sure it's not exposed to either.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Lithium-ion batteries charge fast, but also drain quickly due to phone activity2. Batteries protected from overcharging when plugged in overnight3. Trickle charges during overnight charging can reduce battery capacity4. How best to charge smartphonesVOICEOVER (in English): "Modern smartphones use lithium-ion batteries that charge fast but also get used up quickly because of the sheer amount of mobile activity they power.""People tend to drain their phone batteries before plugging them in overnight. Fortunately, most are equipped with chips that protect against overcharging.""Still, it's unwise to leave a device plugged once its battery is full, since trickle charges can heat up the phone, stressing and wearing down the battery.""Experts recommend charging the phone before it empties completely, and not bringing it to a full charge. Plugging it in occasionally throughout the day ensures the battery retains its capacity longer."SOURCES: Battery University, http://batteryuniversity.com/learn/article/charging_lithium_ion_batterieshttp://time.com/4949569/mobile-phone-charge-overnight/https://www.pcmag.com/news/357987/charging-your-phone-overnight-battery-myths-debunkedhttp://www.businessinsider.com/the-best-way-to-charge-your-iphone-2016-7?utm_content=buffer0401f&utm_medium=social&utm_source=facebook.com&utm_campaign=buffer-ti***]]></description>
