      <title>Austin startup can 3D print cheap houses in less than 24 hours</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA construction tech company is using 3D-printing to provide houses for the 1.2 billion people in the world without adequate housing.Wired reports that Texas startup Icon unveiled a proof-of-concept model house at the annual SXSW innovation festival in Austin. The 650-square-foot structure featured a living room, bedroom, bathroom, and curved porch.Using traditional building methods, a community of a hundred houses will take roughly eight months to complete. But with an industrial-sized Vulcan 3D printer, Icon claims it a single-storey home can be constructed using cement in only 12 to 24 hours.Each 600 to 800 square foot home costs $10,000 to build, but the company is working to drop it to just $4,000.Icon is working with housing charity New Story to bring the printer to El Salvador, where it plans to build a community of 3D printed houses within the year.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Traditional way of building houses2. Houses 3D printed in less than a day3. Size and cost of each 3D printed house4. First model house unveiled in Austin VOICEOVER (in English): "Using traditional building methods, a community of a hundred houses will take roughly eight months to complete.""But with an industrial-sized Vulcan 3D printer, Texas startup Icon claims it can construct a single-storey home using cement in only 12 to 24 hours.""Each 600 to 800 square foot home costs $10,000 to build, but the company is working to drop it to just $4,000.""A proof-of-concept model house unveiled in Austin features a living room, bedroom, and bathroom, along with a curved porch."SOURCES: Icon, Wired, World Resources Institutehttps://www.iconbuild.com/https://www.wired.com/story/new-story-3-d-printed-hous