      <title>Identical twins no longer share same DNA after one spends a year in space</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANIdentical NASA twin astronauts Scott and Mark Kelly no longer share the same DNA after the former spent a year in space.According to NASA, scientists compared the twins' DNA and RNA via whole-genome sequencing. They found that 7% of Scott's DNA had changed into so-called space-genes.His immune system, bone formation and eyesight all went under changes, reported Live Science.Telomeres, caps on chromosomes, typically shorten as a person ages. Kelly's lengthened, according to NASA, but returned to normal two days after he returned to Earth.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of DNA sequencing2. Depiction of DNA sequencing continued and change percentage3. Depiction of changes in Kelly4. Depiction of telomeresVOICEOVER (in English): "Following his year in space, scientists compared the DNA and RNA of Scott Kelly with his identical twin brother Mark via whole-genome sequencing.""They found that 7% of Kelly's DNA had changed into so-called space-genes.""As well as that, Kelly's immune system, bone formation and eyesight all went under changes during his year in space.""Telomeres, caps on chromosomes, typically shorten as a person ages.""NASA found Kelly's lengthened spending a year aboard the International Space Station.""They returned to normal two days after he returned to Earth."SOURCES: NASA, CNN, Live Sciencehttps://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-twins-study-investigators-to-release-integrated-paper-in-2018https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/14/health/scott-kelly-dna-nasa-twins-study/index.htmlhttps://www.livescience.com/62000-scott-kelly-dna-twin-study.html***]]></description>
