      <title>Facebook facing backlash over Cambridge Analytica data misuse</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANFacebook is facing calls for regulation from congress after reports a political consultant gained inappropriate access to 50 million users' data beginning in 2014. The company disclosed the news in a blog post last Friday. American and British lawmakers are demand on Sunday Facebook explain how so many profiles were harvested without the social network notifying users, according to the New York Times. According the New York Times and the Observer, Cambridge Analytica used personal information taken without permission early in 2014 to build a system that could profile US voters, in order more effectively target them with personalized political ads. The data has not been deleted despite Facebook's demands beginning in 2015. Around 270,000 people allowed a researcher to use their personal data, who also scraped the data of all their friends as well, until the end of 2015. The researcher then sold the data to Cambridge Analytica. Cambridge Analytica worked on Trump's 2016 campaign. According to Reuters, a Trump campaign official said it used Republican data sources for voter information, not Cambridge Analytica. Facebook is claiming Cambridge Analytica and researchers were in breach of policy and that it was exploring legal action. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of Facebook data breach2. Depiction of Cambridge Analytica using FB data to make political ads3. Researcher using data on 270,000 users to access all their friends too4. The user data was then sold to Cambridge AnalyticaVOICEOVER (in English): "Facebook is facing calls for regulation from congress after reports that a political consultant gained inappropriate access to 50 million users' data beginning in 2014." 