      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANDespite being delayed by the Pyeongchang Winter Olympics, the annual war games on the democratic side of the Korean Peninsula are pushing through.According to Korea JoongAng Daily, South Korea and the U.S. have announced that joint military drills between the two countries will begin on April 1.The war games consist of two drills. The first, called "Foal Eagle", is a series of field-training exercises combining ground, air, naval, and special operations.The four-week-long program involves 290,000 South Korean and 11,500 American troops.The second drill, called "Key Resolve", is a computer-simulated command post exercise that's set to be held for two weeks starting April 23.This year's war games are more low-key compared to previous years, possibly to avoid provoking North Korea, who has always objected to them.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. US and South Korea to begin joint military exercises on April 12. Depiction of Foal Eagle drill3. 290,000 South Korean and 11,500 US troops involved in Foal Eagle4. Depiction of Key Resolve computer-simulated training programVOICEOVER (in English): "South Korea  and the U.S. have announced that joint military drills between the two countries will begin on April 1.""The war games consist of two drills. The first, called 'Foal Eagle', is a series of field training exercises combining ground, air, naval, and special operations.""The four-week-long program involves 290,000 South Korean and 11,500 American troops.""The second drill, called 'Key Resolve', is a computer-simulated command post exercise that's set to be held for two weeks starting April 23."SOURCES: CNBC, Korea JoongAng Daily, Los Angeles Timeshttps://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/20/us-sou