      <title>Archaeologists find 81 ancient settlements in the Amazon</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANThe Amazon was believed to be largely uninhabited before Europeans arrived in South America, but new research shows this may not be the case.According to a study published in Nature Communications, deforestation in the Amazon has uncovered at least 81 geoglyphs  trenches carved into the ground. They were spotted on satellite images of Brazil's Upper Tapajos Basin.The geoglyphs come in a range of different shapes and sizes, and are believed to date back centuries, from the years 1250 to 1500.Archaeologists examined several locations and found fragments of pottery, stone axes, and fertile dark earth indicative of a long-term human settlement.Researchers used models to estimate that between 1,000 to 1,500 wooden settlements were built in the southern rim of the Amazon alone, housing 500,000 to a million people.This indigenous population was likely wiped out by the outbreak of diseases, and would have been worsened by the arrival of the Europeans.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Discovery of 81 geoglyphs in deforested areas of the Amazon2. Settlements of different shapes and sizes, from years 1250 to 15003. Archaeologists finding fragments that indicate long-term human habitation4. Settlement structures possibly made from woodVOICEOVER (in English): "Deforestation in the Amazon has uncovered at least 81 geoglyphs- trenches carved into the ground that were spotted on satellite images of Brazil's Upper Tapajos Basin.""The geoglyphs come in a range of different shapes and sizes, and are believed to date back centuries, from the years 1250 to 1500.""Archaeologists examined several locations and found fragments of pottery, stone axes, and fertile dark earth indicative of a long-term human settlement.""Researchers used models to estimate that between 1,000 to 1,500 wooden settlements were built in the southern rim of the Amazon alone, housing 500,000 to a million people."SOURCES: Nature Communications, Washington Post, The Guardianhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-018-03510-7https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2018/03/27/archaeologists-discover-81-ancient-settlements-in-the-amazon/?utm_term=.b6e9cc6b8bd9https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/mar/27/lost-amazon-villages-uncovered-by-archaeologists***]]></description>
