      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA Japanese startup wants to offer the world on-demand fake meteor showers.Tokyo-based Astro Live Experience will use a microsatellite to create an artificial shooting star show for the 2020 Olympics. The company now want to make it available on demand.In December, the company plans to launch a to two satellites at an orbit of 220 miles over Earth. The International Space Station orbits at 250 miles. The heights of other the thousands of other satellites in orbit vary."ALE told BuzzFeed they'd do a triple-check with US Strategic Command's satellite trajectory prior to any pellet launch in order to avoid collision with other spacecraft.The problem with that, a retired U.S. Air Force Colonel pointed out, is that spy satellites' trajectories are classified and kept out of the catalog. Meaning, a pellet could theoretically hit one.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of shooting stars2. Depiction of artificial shooting stars over Tokyo3. Depiction of satellite and pellets4. Depiction of satellite and pellet in space5. Depiction of pellets as artificial shooting stars.6. Depiction of December launch7. Depiction of multiple satellites8. Depiction of pellet colliding with satelliteVOICEOVER (in English): SOURCES: Star-ALE, Futurism, BuzzFeed, TechTimes, Christian Science Monitor, Facebook / Now This, Phys.orghttp://star-ale.comhttps://www.buzzfeed.com/danvergano/ale-shooting-star-satellite-meteor?utm_term=.ip31RlK88#.acKV7YA88https://futurism.com/meteor-showers-demand-rich-people/https://www.nbcnews.com/mach/science/demand-meteor-showers-may-be-way-ncna860466http://www.techtimes.com/articles/160172/20160523/what-you-need-to-know-about-the-pellets-for-japans-man-made-meteor-shower